to save an address we store it in a pointer
A pointer is simply the address of a piece of data in memory. A pointer variable is a variable that stores the address of that piece of data. Like any other variable it needs to be declared. General form is:
var_type *var;

the * is what points the "var" as a pointer variable 
that points to a var_type.
the value of var will be a memory address holding a value type var_type

int *ptr
ptr is the name of the variable of type point to an integer.

char *ptr2 points to character

float *ptr3 points to a float 

etc

